This paper proposes a framework for constructing graph neural networks (GNNs) and evaluates its performance on various tasks. The paper focuses on the aggregation of features from node neighborhoods, which is a common theme in GNN research. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), which is the primary area of research for GNNs. Additionally, the paper discusses the discriminative power and feature representation capabilities of GNNs, which suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also evaluates its framework on graph classification and regression tasks, which are common in computer vision (cs.CV) and natural language processing (cs.CL). Finally, the paper proposes a systematic approach to constructing GNNs, which could be relevant to neural networks (cs.NE) research.
